  <div class="stage-intro">
    <h2>About this stage</h2>
    <p><strong>The asymmetry is deliberate.</strong> Suppliers must demonstrate they meet minimum standards before they can operate on the platform. Commissioners face the opposite: barriers are removed, support is provided, the aim is to make participation as easy as possible.</p>
    <p><strong>Supplier onboarding:</strong> Evidence packs, IG compliance (DPIA, data controller model), clinical safety (DCB0129/DCB0160), MHRA registration where applicable, the Supplier Onboarding Framework. Single reusable gateway rather than per-commissioner reassurance.</p>
    <p><strong>Commissioner enablement:</strong> Ready-made business cases, pathway templates, integration support, dedicated onboarding contacts. Zero friction for a commissioner who wants to offer home testing to their population.</p>
    <div class="asymmetry-callout">Suppliers face a gateway. Commissioners face an open door.</div>
  <div class="holding-q">
    <div class="holding-q-h">Open Q for SLT &middot; pathology lab dual position</div>
    <strong>Pathology labs sit in two places at once.</strong> They are clinical infrastructure under Aisha's safety governance (sample analysis, result generation, turnaround SLAs) AND they are suppliers in Joe's contract framework. The model has not yet resolved which territory holds the contract. <em>Open Q: do pathology contracts run through the HomeTest framework as suppliers, or sit outside it as clinical infrastructure that HomeTest plugs into? The answer affects procurement vehicle, tariff treatment, and the assurance bar applied at this stage.</em>
  </div>

  </div>

  <h2 class="section-title">Current Status</h2>

  <!-- SUPPLIER SIDE -->
  <div class="split-block">
    <div class="split-block-header supplier">
      &#9650; Supplier Side <span class="desc">Filtered and held to account</span>
    </div>
    <div class="split-block-body">

      <div class="status-section progress-section">
        <div class="status-heading heading-progress">
          <span class="status-dot dot-progress"></span>
          In Progress
          <span class="status-count">5 items</span>
        </div>
        <ul class="status-list progress">
          <li>DPIA: parts 1-4 reviewed with amendments. Cross-functional workshop completed. Actions assigned: update data flow diagram with beta cohort selection process, condense DPIA narrative and move data field details to addendum, review technical controls and security wording, clarify audit logging. Direction-required question for Private Beta back open pending Privacy, Trust and Transparency (PTT) confirmation. Caldicott Guardian review assumed not needed but unconfirmed. Target sign-off: end June 2026.</li>
          <li><strong>Public beta DPIA scope decision (agreed in principle):</strong> include Pathway 2 (acute-initiated, e.g. PSA-AS) and Pathway 3 (GP-initiated, e.g. iron deficiency anaemia) in the public beta DPIA documentation, with the right to descope Pathway 3 first and Pathway 2 second if complexity threatens launch. Decision logic: data flows for Pathway 2 are not materially different from Pathway 1; the wider precedent is to ask for the full scope upfront rather than return for incremental directions later.</li>
          <li>DSA work with LAs and suppliers ongoing. Template DSA being developed. Initial LA IG engagement met pushback, redirecting to service channel. Future IG requests to be routed through service leads, not IG teams directly</li>
          <li>Clinical safety: hazard log (8 hazards across 4 groupings) and System Level Security Policy (SLSP) in progress. GDS Alpha Assessment complete. SH:24 submitted HomeTest-specific Clinical Safety Case</li>
          <li>Supplier eligibility criteria being shaped. Commercial, clinical and IG entry criteria need to be defined and published so suppliers can self-assess before engaging the framework</li>
          <li>Supplier Onboarding Framework: two straw-man documents created as a starting point. Cover the intended onboarding journey at a high level: pre-qualification, evidence pack submission, IG and clinical safety gateway, commercial terms, technical integration, and go-live readiness. Early-stage scaffolding only, not final artefacts, not yet in operational use</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="status-section open-section">
        <div class="status-heading heading-open">
          <span class="status-dot dot-open"></span>
          Open Decisions
          <span class="status-count">6 items</span>
        </div>
        <ul class="status-list open">
          <li>Minimum supplier standards not yet codified. Direction agreed that these should include accreditation requirements, not just self-declaration. Quality assurance framework needs to define what 'good' looks like before suppliers can be measured against it</li>
          <li>Clinical accountability model: where does accountability sit at each touch point in the patient journey?</li>
          <li>Offboarding trigger criteria and process: what happens when a supplier fails to meet standards?</li>
          <li>Information Asset Owner (IAO) appointment: CRITICAL BLOCKER. PTT requires the IAO to be a permanent NHSE employee. Programme heavily contractor-staffed. SRO on maternity leave with deputy in place. Information Asset Administrator (IAA) governance also unresolved. No timeline for resolution. DPIA cannot be approved without IAO sign-off</li>
          <li>Supplier Onboarding Framework: drafted in April 2026 (Strawman v0.1). Suppliers self-assess against the published criteria pack, submit, clear the assurance gate. Alpha suppliers (Preventx, SH:24) admitted under earlier route may need to complete retroactively.</li>
          <li>IG resourcing: broader governance gaps beyond IAO. PTT capacity constrained across NHS</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

